<DOC><DOCNO> AP890512-0239 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-12-89 0108EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-12 0795</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0836</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Retail sales rose by a lackluster 0.4 percentin April, the government said in a report cited by analysts asevidence that higher interest rates are taking a toll on economicgrowth.   The Commerce Department said Thursday sales climbed to aseasonally adjusted $139.9 billion last month after remaining flatin March and falling 0.4 percent in February.   Economists had expected a much stronger rebound in April,anticipating a surge of between 1 percent and 2 percent on thestrength of higher auto sales.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Depositors withdrew a net $8.5 billion fromthe nation's savings and loans in March, the government says. Theoutflow was more than $2 billion below January's record, but stillconsidered very large.   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Thursday the March outflowcompared with $9.2 billion in February and a record $10.8 billionin January. It was the 11th month of withdrawals in a row and thefifth of withdrawals in excess of $7 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Arthur Levitt Jr. said he was resigning aschairman of the American Stock Exchange after 11 years at thenation's third-largest stock market, which has attempted to stemthe loss of business to its bigger Wall Street peers by expandinginto innovative new securities.   Levitt, 58, said Thursday he would remain at the exchange untila successor was named. He said he plans to build his 3-year-oldLevitt Communications Inc. into a larger publishing company.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Senate and House negotiators agreed on a $1.17trillion budget for fiscal 1990.   The spending plan constrains the Pentagon, treats many domesticprograms generously and leaves many prickly decisions for later.Both houses are expected to give final approval to the documentnext week.   Bargainers from the House and Senate agreed to the documentThursday on only their second day of public meetings.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Exxon Corp. said it would go along with many ofthe changes some of its shareholders suggested to better preparefor future environmental disasters in the wake of its Alaskan oilspill.   Exxon said Thursday it will recommend its board of directorsapprove setting up a new committee to review corporate policies andprograms related to worker safety and the environment.   In addition, Exxon said it would consider spending more money onenvironmental research and pollution prevention. About $5.5 billionhas been spent in that area from 1970 to 1988, it said.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Amway Corp. plans to spin off Avon ProductsInc.'s retail operation, comprising the popular Giorgio perfume andother fragrances, if its $2 billion-plus takeover bid for Avonsucceeds.   Amway disclosed the plan in a document submitted to theSecurities and Exchange Commission. It said it would retain Avon'sworldwide direct selling division if acquires its much larger rival.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House has voted in favor of raising theminimum wage to $4.55 an hour by October 1991, leaving only a finalSenate vote before the bill goes to President Bush, who haspromised to veto it.   Bush insists that the minimum should be raised only to $4.25 byJanuary 1992 _ and then only if the proposal allows employers topay a lower ``training wage'' to new workers for six months.   The minimum is now $3.35, where it has been since 1981.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee votednarrowly to approve the $7 billion FSX deal involving jointU.S.-Japanese development and production of a next-generationfighter for Japan.   On a 9-8 vote, the committee Thursday rejected a resolution todisapprove the deal, which has generated sharp criticism on CapitolHill over technology and economic issues.   Action then shifted to the Senate floor, where FSX opponentsvoiced hope they would still be able to muster majority support forthe disapproval resolution.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A generic-drug company executive accused theFood and Drug Administration of holding up approvals of itsproducts to retaliate against the firm for having sparked aninvestigation into alleged bribery at the agency.   Roy McKnight, chairman of Mylan Laboratories in Pittsburgh, tolda House subcommittee the company has met all the regulatoryrequirements for approval to make a number of drugs at its newPuerto Rico plant, drugs for which Mylan has approval to make atother plants.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices rose slightly Thursday in restrained trading thatreflected uncertainties over news from Panama, the progress of aTreasury debt auction and an upcoming report on inflation. The DowJones average of 30 industrials rose 8.43 to 2,382.88.   Bond prices rose following three days of declines. The dollaralso gained.   Crude oil futures climbed back above $20 a barrel.</TEXT></DOC>